unity, defying the notion of nationalism as a direct consequence of ethnicity.Baumann asks what made individuals into determined nationalists in the first place, revealing the close link to private lives, including intimate family dramas and scandals. He looks at how nationalism emerged from domestic spaces, and how women played an important (if often invisible) role in fin-de-siècle politics. Dynasty Divided explains how nineteenth-century Kievans cultivated their national self-images and how, by the twentieth century, Ukraine steered away from Russia. The two branches of this family of Russian nationalists and Ukrainian nationalists epitomize the struggles for modern Ukraine.  afunded by Swiss National Science Foundation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNationalismzRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismzRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzUkrainexHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismzUkrainexHistoryy20th century. 4aHISTORY. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aRussian Ukrainian split family, Shulgin family history, Ukrainian nationalism, Russian nationalism, Kiev nationalism, Shul'hyns, Russo-Ukrainian War, Russia Ukraine conflict, nineteenth-century Eastern Europe.2 aSwiss National Science Foundationefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501770951zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501770951zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501770951/original  a978-3-11-075183-3 Cornell Universi